277
00:22:26,920 --> 00:22:32,320
So as a final question along this topic of 
building out PMs, hiring PMs for the first time,  

278
00:22:32,320 --> 00:22:36,240
for someone that's still like, "I don't know, I 
don't really want product managers at my company  

279
00:22:36,240 --> 00:22:41,080
and they're just so annoying.", what is it that 
you think people most miss about the value that  

280
00:22:41,080 --> 00:22:47,240
a PM brings to your org that may be a sign? 
"Oh, okay, I see. Maybe we do need this."

281
00:22:47,240 --> 00:22:51,760
All right, so I think there's different kinds 
of PMs and different flavors of PMs. One thing  

282
00:22:51,760 --> 00:23:01,080
that I really, I feel like sometimes gets lost in 
when we talk about, oh, I've met one PM and they  

283
00:23:01,080 --> 00:23:05,520
kind of didn't do what I wanted them to do or they 
didn't work in the way that I wanted them to work,  

284
00:23:05,520 --> 00:23:10,320
so therefore, all PMs suck. There's a problem 
with that because there's just so many different  

285
00:23:10,320 --> 00:23:14,240
flavors of what a product manager is, and 
it depends on the company, it depends on the  

286
00:23:14,240 --> 00:23:19,760
industry, it depends on the role within a company.
And so a framework that I really like using to  

287
00:23:19,760 --> 00:23:25,440
determine, okay, what kind of PM do you need 
and then hire for that is something that I  

288
00:23:25,440 --> 00:23:31,560
learned at Square. We use this idea of a pioneer, 
a town settler, and a city planner. And that idea  

289
00:23:31,560 --> 00:23:36,760
is like, okay, so the pioneer is a PM that's 
really good at zero to one, they can create  

290
00:23:36,760 --> 00:23:41,600
something from nothing. You're pioneering into 
this uncharted territory. There's nothing there  

291
00:23:41,600 --> 00:23:45,440
for you. There's not any sort of infrastructure. 
You're building it from scratch. You're kind of  

292
00:23:45,440 --> 00:23:49,560
taking natural resources and seeing how you 
can reapply them into building what you need  

293
00:23:49,560 --> 00:23:56,200
in order to survive and then hopefully grow.
The town settler PM is in that growth stage of  

294
00:23:56,200 --> 00:24:01,560
maturity of a product. They're really working 
on, again, to use the same metaphor, I guess,  

295
00:24:01,560 --> 00:24:06,560
you're in a town, there might be a bank, there 
might be a post office, there might be a school,  

296
00:24:06,560 --> 00:24:11,360
and there might be some gravel roads, but nothing 
more than that. And so you have some level of  

297
00:24:11,360 --> 00:24:16,200
infrastructure, but what you're trying to do 
is further grow the town that you're building  

298
00:24:16,200 --> 00:24:21,400
out and put in some foundational elements but 
also try to do some experiments. Maybe things  

299
00:24:21,400 --> 00:24:25,320
don't work out exactly the way you want, but 
then you also want to build for the future. 

300
00:24:25,320 --> 00:24:29,760
And then a city planner is a PM that's really 
good at mature products, really good at driving  

301
00:24:29,760 --> 00:24:34,520
efficiencies at scale. They have the city. 
Everything that they do touches hundreds,  

302
00:24:34,520 --> 00:24:39,240
thousands, millions of customers immediately. And 
so the type of PM that you need for something like  

303
00:24:39,240 --> 00:24:44,560
that is going to be very different than a zero to 
one PM. And so when people, especially founders  

304
00:24:44,560 --> 00:24:49,320
say, "I don't want a PM.", I think it's because 
they're thinking of a mature city planner when  

305
00:24:49,320 --> 00:24:55,800
they could find a former entrepreneur, a former 
founder, a good pioneer to build out the next  

306
00:24:55,800 --> 00:25:00,160
set of products, or they really need somebody 
who's great at growth and starting to put some  

307
00:25:00,160 --> 00:25:06,480
of the process in but not build it to the point 
of I'm a big mature enterprise company anymore.

308
00:25:06,480 --> 00:25:13,000
I love this metaphor. And is the advice that 
as the smaller you are, the earlier in the  

309
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:17,120
spectrum you want to be hiring? More pioneers 
and a few town settlers as you build your team?

310
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:21,720
Probably. I think it just really depends on 
what you're hiring for. Even for Mercury,  

311
00:25:21,720 --> 00:25:28,680
we had our banking, core banking services, we're 
still a mature product in our spectrum. Everything  

312
00:25:28,680 --> 00:25:32,840
that we do there, we have to truly not even 
measure it twice, measure it three times,  

313
00:25:32,840 --> 00:25:38,000
cut once, be really sure about what we're doing. 
And that scale and the ability to have a PM that  

314
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:42,120
can think about all of that scale is really 
important. And so you really want to test  

315
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:48,240
out have they done it before? Do they know what 
they're talking about? And then in which case,  

316
00:25:48,240 --> 00:25:52,440
were you willing to take riskier bets versus 
being really conservative about what you're  

317
00:25:52,440 --> 00:25:59,160
doing and then determine what kind of PM you need 
for it. Because otherwise, you see the resumes,  

318
00:25:59,160 --> 00:26:02,360
you see what they say they've done. 
But when you've talked to somebody,  

319
00:26:02,360 --> 00:26:06,680
when you're interviewing someone, really try to 
drill into what kind of experience they are good  

320
00:26:06,680 --> 00:26:11,760
at, what they want in their next role, because 
otherwise, the resume without the receipt is just  

321
00:26:11,760 --> 00:26:16,280
a piece of paper and you want to get the receipts. 
What's the work that they've actually done?

322
00:26:16,280 --> 00:26:20,920
Following this thread, I asked a bunch of people 
that work with you at Mercury and Block what to  

323
00:26:20,920 --> 00:26:27,040
ask you. And one of the questions that I loved 
came from the COO of Mercury, Jason Zhang. And  

324
00:26:27,040 --> 00:26:32,120
his question was, what do you think attracts 
great product managers and great talents to  

325
00:26:32,120 --> 00:26:38,680
a company? What makes them hungry to join your 
company? How do they hire a Rohini, basically?

326
00:26:38,680 --> 00:26:43,480
Okay, there's a few answers to this. Maybe just 
starting off, let's take away some of the table  

327
00:26:43,480 --> 00:26:49,320
stakes. Let's assume that candidates know that the 
company's viable, it's doing well, paying market  

328
00:26:49,320 --> 00:26:55,080
rates, all of that. The candidate and the product 
have good... There's a resonance with that. The  

329
00:26:55,080 --> 00:27:01,400
culture has good vibe checks. So taking away kind 
of the table stakes of hiring, I think there's a  

330
00:27:01,400 --> 00:27:05,920
couple things from the company side and then the 
candidate side. I think from the company side,  

331
00:27:05,920 --> 00:27:10,280
it really boils down to do you understand the 
candidates that are coming through the door,  

332
00:27:10,280 --> 00:27:15,120
especially when you're hiring for seniority and 
experience, you kind of have to take it like a  

333
00:27:15,120 --> 00:27:19,360
product manager would think about this problem 
and say, "All right, if this is my customer,  

334
00:27:19,360 --> 00:27:25,960
what's their goal? What's their jobs to be 
done?" kind of an idea and consider where the  

335
00:27:25,960 --> 00:27:32,120
PMs would be that you're hiring for on this...
Actually, a mentor of mine had this great  

336
00:27:32,120 --> 00:27:37,600
framework. He said that every career follows 
this S-curve. And if you think about the Y  

337
00:27:37,600 --> 00:27:44,520
axis being kind of level of ambiguity, X axis 
being level of scale, you start off in this S,  

338
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:48,320
kind of near the origin, and you're usually 
trying, especially when you're just starting  

339
00:27:48,320 --> 00:27:54,320
off in the discipline or your career, you have one 
project, low ambiguity, and you're just saying,  

340
00:27:54,320 --> 00:27:59,800
"Can I do this one thing? Can I fix onboarding?" 
There's only so many different ways to cut that  

341
00:27:59,800 --> 00:28:04,520
up and do it. And you know the goal, it's 
a defined goal. You're just kind of driving  

342
00:28:04,520 --> 00:28:10,320
towards being able to make these improvements or 
make it better, make it better designed, whatever  

343
00:28:10,320 --> 00:28:15,240
you need to be doing. It's like this one project. 
And then you kind move around along that S at the  

344
00:28:15,240 --> 00:28:19,280
bottom and you're doing multiple projects with 
low ambiguity still, but can you handle multiple  

345
00:28:19,280 --> 00:28:23,400
things and juggle them all at the same time?
At some point, you get into this inflection  

346
00:28:23,400 --> 00:28:28,440
point and you have this one really ambiguous 
problem set at some point in your career it's like  

347
00:28:28,440 --> 00:28:34,120
10X revenue in 12 months. There's a lot of 
different ways you could probably do that, but  

348
00:28:34,120 --> 00:28:38,360
there's a lot of wrong ways to probably do that. 
And there's a few right ways and you got to figure  

349
00:28:38,360 --> 00:28:44,120
out which way is up and there's just so much 
ambiguity and you just don't know how to maybe  

350
00:28:44,120 --> 00:28:48,920
do that immediately. But that's the challenge for 
that part of your S-curve. And then at another  

351
00:28:48,920 --> 00:28:53,760
scale, it's like towards the top of that S, 
you're pretty much just doing all ambiguous  

352
00:28:53,760 --> 00:28:58,520
projects or problems at scale. That's all that 
hits you. So you think of a VP of product CPO  

353
00:28:58,520 --> 00:29:02,440
kind of level. All it is is strategic questions 
that you don't know the answers to and have to  

354
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:10,480
figure that out across 10 or 12 different topics.
And so I think going back to how to attract these  

355
00:29:10,480 --> 00:29:15,080
types of talent, know where on the S-curve they 
are and what's their next step in that S-curve  

356
00:29:15,080 --> 00:29:21,280
because then you can say, "All right, I can then 
give you a fun challenge for what you need next in  

357
00:29:21,280 --> 00:29:27,920
your career." I think senior folks want to know, 
is a problem area big enough? Is it meaty enough  

358
00:29:27,920 --> 00:29:33,080
where I wake up every day and I get to be working 
on this scope and working to serve these types of  

359
00:29:33,080 --> 00:29:38,000
customers? Will it challenge me? Will it make me 
a better PM? Those are the considerations that  

360
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:44,760
they're making. And then the second consideration 
is who do I get to work with? So we actually kind  

361
00:29:44,760 --> 00:29:50,640
of talked about this in a recent post that we 
wrote for your newsletter of the functional types  

362
00:29:50,640 --> 00:29:55,240
of organizational structures. And I think when 
you have a functional structure within your org,  

363
00:29:55,240 --> 00:29:59,240
it's really nice because then, you can say, "oh, 
I get to work with these types of PMs because  

364
00:29:59,240 --> 00:30:06,000
there's a product lead, there's a product group."
And I play tennis. You want to play tennis,  

365
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:10,000
you want to challenge yourself with people that 
are a little bit better than you and bounce that  

366
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:14,000
ball back and forth and it's fun. And the same 
thing goes for the functional leads within design  

367
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:17,280
and eng because those are going to be your peer 
groups. You want to make sure that you're working  

368
00:30:17,280 --> 00:30:25,440
with folks that are excited and are fulfilled 
by doing this kind of work. And so for me, it  

