550
00:46:24,600 --> 00:46:30,480
And so a lot of exciting stuff. We're still in 
the early days of building out the SaaS model,  

551
00:46:30,480 --> 00:46:36,120
building out personal banking, but lots more to 
come. So excited for where Mercury is set up for  

552
00:46:36,120 --> 00:46:41,880
in the next few quarters. Going into some of maybe 
the biggest lessons learned about going from one  

553
00:46:41,880 --> 00:46:48,480
product to multi-product, probably two general 
categories. One, the organizational structure  

554
00:46:48,480 --> 00:46:54,560
is really important and probably as important as 
just the product decisions, and the organizational  

555
00:46:54,560 --> 00:47:01,960
culture is also important. So one thing we learned 
was having new product areas, new seedlings being  

556
00:47:01,960 --> 00:47:09,040
too close within the true org structure to the 
core banking or payments or mature products, made  

557
00:47:09,040 --> 00:47:14,320
it hard for that new product to even grow because 
they were always being pulled in, sucked in. 

558
00:47:14,320 --> 00:47:19,680
The gravitational force of a more mature 
product always had prioritization work,  

559
00:47:19,680 --> 00:47:24,680
maintenance work, things that were more impactful 
to be done. And so their roadmaps would always get  

560
00:47:24,680 --> 00:47:32,320
trumped by any of that. So it didn't afford 
any space for seedlings to grow. And yeah,  

561
00:47:32,320 --> 00:47:37,880
this idea of when you have this small little fire, 
you want to give it air in order for it to truly  

562
00:47:37,880 --> 00:47:44,280
blossom to a flame. And so the organizational 
structure really gives these teams that space.  

563
00:47:44,280 --> 00:47:49,080
We actually created completely different orgs. 
This is why my team exists as an expansion org  

564
00:47:49,080 --> 00:47:52,960
because it is completely separate from 
some of the more mature product teams.

565
00:47:52,960 --> 00:47:57,120
And when you say separate 
dedicated resources on this project  

566
00:47:57,120 --> 00:48:01,120
for some number of... What's the 
timeframe you give new seedlings?

567
00:48:01,120 --> 00:48:07,960
We're thinking of these as small seed stage 
companies and every quarter, every half year,  

568
00:48:07,960 --> 00:48:13,000
we look at them as like, do we want to keep 
investing? And so there's no end time for  

569
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:18,560
them to ever move back into the mature products 
until they become, I don't know, series C company  

570
00:48:18,560 --> 00:48:23,760
in and of themselves. So we're not really 
looking at an end time. We're just saying,  

571
00:48:23,760 --> 00:48:28,280
"You have this dedicated team. We'll continue 
investing and providing headcount and whatever  

572
00:48:28,280 --> 00:48:34,520
you need as this product, this business 
line shows the path towards success."

573
00:48:34,520 --> 00:48:38,600
And I think that point is really important. 
So it's basically every quarter/two quarters,  

574
00:48:38,600 --> 00:48:41,520
you check in, how's this going? Do you agree to,  

575
00:48:41,520 --> 00:48:44,080
here's a milestone that we're 
looking for in the next quarter,  

576
00:48:44,080 --> 00:48:48,400
six months? Do you make it super concrete? Is it 
pretty qualitative? How do you think about that?

577
00:48:48,400 --> 00:48:52,760
We have goals and we also allow these teams... 
They're so early that the learnings are really  

578
00:48:52,760 --> 00:48:56,960
important. It's just like an angel investment. 
There's going to be pivots, we realize that.  

579
00:48:56,960 --> 00:49:02,680
We're not saying that we're going to kill it if 
it doesn't hit X. But we do have goals in mind,  

580
00:49:02,680 --> 00:49:04,800
we have financial projections in mind, and we say,  

581
00:49:04,800 --> 00:49:07,920
"If you don't hit that, what's the 
key learning that we've made that  

582
00:49:07,920 --> 00:49:12,880
we think we can still hit something in that 
general direction in the next six months?".

583
00:49:12,880 --> 00:49:17,440
And what does a seed team look like generally? 
What are the resources you put into it?

584
00:49:17,440 --> 00:49:25,360
I mean, it's the full cross-functional 
squads of eng, design, product, data science,  

585
00:49:25,360 --> 00:49:30,360
everyone that you probably need. And then we 
have cross-functional overlaps with our core  

586
00:49:30,360 --> 00:49:36,080
teams across the company. So sometimes 
we will have dedicated... If we need a  

587
00:49:36,080 --> 00:49:41,200
dedicated CS or dedicated risk or dedicated 
ops folks on these teams. But usually,  

588
00:49:41,200 --> 00:49:47,000
it's just leverage the central teams that 
already exist for some of those functions.

589
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:50,440
And how many engineers do you usually 
try to put on a seed investment?

590
00:49:50,440 --> 00:49:56,160
It kind of depends. Our personal banking 
product has a lot more engineers,  

591
00:49:56,160 --> 00:49:59,840
probably 3X than maybe our invoicing product line.

592
00:49:59,840 --> 00:50:01,480
Even at the beginning?

593
00:50:01,480 --> 00:50:06,640
Well, so I think seeding that, it just required... 
We were going after a completely different market.  

594
00:50:06,640 --> 00:50:12,320
We were going after a different base, and having 
another banking solution, while we still had one,  

595
00:50:12,320 --> 00:50:15,240
we took a lot of the learnings and efforts 
that the business banking side did,  

596
00:50:15,240 --> 00:50:19,160
but we had to build a bunch of that. 
And so the initial investment just was  

597
00:50:19,160 --> 00:50:24,840
a different request. Whereas in invoicing, 
we're building the software on top of the  

598
00:50:24,840 --> 00:50:30,800
banking and it requires a different level 
in order to get to minimal lovable product.  

599
00:50:30,800 --> 00:50:36,400
And so we're giving the teams just 
enough, but we want them to stretch.

600
00:50:36,400 --> 00:50:42,240
And I feel like there's also a connection to how 
big this opportunity is invoicing versus becoming  

601
00:50:42,240 --> 00:50:48,240
the new personal bank of the world. So it makes 
sense. Let's put a few more resources on this one.

602
00:50:48,240 --> 00:50:53,520
Right. Absolutely. I would say I think the PMs on 
those teams both want world domination. So yeah.

603
00:50:54,040 --> 00:50:55,520
Let's not hit on invoicing.

604
00:50:55,520 --> 00:50:56,000
Yeah.

605
00:50:56,000 --> 00:51:03,920
Okay. I understand. Okay, so specifically, they 
hired you to create this carve out almost for  

606
00:51:03,920 --> 00:51:07,800
new product investments. I think that's 
a really cool lesson. Just hire a leader  

607
00:51:07,800 --> 00:51:12,760
that is overseeing all of these new seed 
bets versus just a team off to the side.

608
00:51:12,760 --> 00:51:18,920
Yes. I think that kind of hits that culture that 
needed to be instilled into this organization too,  

609
00:51:18,920 --> 00:51:23,040
because we're going to be a zero to one team and 
we're going to have to work in a little bit of a  

610
00:51:23,040 --> 00:51:28,520
different way. Our counterparts on the core 
mature products will use monthly development  

611
00:51:28,520 --> 00:51:33,400
cycles. They'll figure out their roadmap for the 
month and then just start executing on it. I could  

612
00:51:33,400 --> 00:51:39,440
not find a way in which... I wouldn't know what 
was changing in a month. And so we had to move  

613
00:51:39,440 --> 00:51:44,520
towards two-week sprints and then weekly check-ins 
with a bunch of our work just to stay as nimble as  

614
00:51:44,520 --> 00:51:50,880
possible. We wanted to be able to learn, iterate, 
repeat, and we also have a really heavy-handed  

615
00:51:50,880 --> 00:51:56,840
culture of customer calls, customer research 
that the PMs needed to do. There's just much more  

616
00:51:56,840 --> 00:52:01,720
kind of touch point, pulse check with who these 
customers are. We're going after adjacent areas,  

617
00:52:01,720 --> 00:52:07,800
and so make sure that as a team, you know what 
your customer needs and why it's important.

618
00:52:07,800 --> 00:52:11,200
Can you share more about this 
customer call culture for folks  

619
00:52:11,200 --> 00:52:13,840
that maybe want to learn from how you do it?

620
00:52:13,840 --> 00:52:19,720
It's kind of like, I don't know, just the 
heartbeat of how we operate. So it almost feels so  

621
00:52:19,720 --> 00:52:25,800
natural that I'm not sure if I can impart any new 
learnings on it, but it's like I kind of expect a  

622
00:52:25,800 --> 00:52:31,360
customer conversation at least one a week from the 
team. That seems like such a low bar to me that  

623
00:52:31,360 --> 00:52:36,720
I think the teams do close to... Some teams, when 
they're really into discovery mode, are doing 20,  

624
00:52:36,720 --> 00:52:43,640
25 calls with people. It's wild. Or even just 
going through surveys and understanding what  

625
00:52:43,640 --> 00:52:47,480
qualitative info that they're getting from the 
surveys, quantitative info that they're getting  

626
00:52:47,480 --> 00:52:52,680
from it. I think all of that really counts.
We're customer obsessed at Mercury and so  

627
00:52:52,680 --> 00:52:56,760
you'll even see it like Immad will 
talk to folks on Twitter or on X  

628
00:52:56,760 --> 00:53:03,400
directly. We'll get pings from different folks 
across the company. We'll look at why people off  

629
00:53:03,400 --> 00:53:09,280
boarded with us and we get those messages in a 
Slack channel and it just kind of hits whenever  

630
00:53:09,280 --> 00:53:14,320
it happens in real time. And so all of those 
pieces are customer touch points in my mind,  

631
00:53:14,320 --> 00:53:19,840
and so it's like get on a call with CS, get on 
a call with RMs, drive those calls yourself,  

632
00:53:19,840 --> 00:53:24,240
but just learn as much as you can from what 
our customers need and what they're doing.

633
00:53:24,240 --> 00:53:26,960
I'm going to follow us through 
a little bit more because one,  

634
00:53:26,960 --> 00:53:30,080
a lot of companies say, "We're customer 
obsessed, our teams are customer obsessed,  

635
00:53:30,080 --> 00:53:34,720
we talk to customers all the time." But 
they still build bad stuff. What do you  

636
00:53:34,720 --> 00:53:38,960
think they often miss that maybe you're doing 
that companies you've seen actually that really  

637
00:53:38,960 --> 00:53:44,880
are obsessed and do this well, that often is 
missed when people think they're doing this?

638
00:53:44,880 --> 00:53:49,680
I think there's a little bit of what a customer 
says versus what they want are going to be two  

639
00:53:49,680 --> 00:53:55,760
different things. I think there's just so 
many inputs to all of this, but if you take  

640
00:53:55,760 --> 00:53:59,640
just a conversation, people are really nice, 
especially when they're talking on the phone,  

641
00:53:59,640 --> 00:54:03,320
they'll be really nice. They'll say nice things 
about your product. They'll tell you that they  

642
00:54:03,320 --> 00:54:08,200
messed up and the UX is great, you built it the 
right way and they were doing something wrong, and  

643
00:54:08,200 --> 00:54:13,040
they try to take some of that pressure off of you.
And what you don't want is to go into a  

644
00:54:13,040 --> 00:54:17,080
conversation with a bias. You want to be a 
researcher, you want to be this third party  

645
00:54:17,080 --> 00:54:22,480
non-judgmental, kind of like being brought into 
the jungle and just watching what's happening.  

646
00:54:22,480 --> 00:54:29,960
You're an observer, you're being a documentarian. 
It's not about getting your biases checked or  

647
00:54:29,960 --> 00:54:35,200
validated or invalidated, but it's like just 
understand what it is that the customer's  

648
00:54:35,200 --> 00:54:40,800
trying to do, what context they were trying to 
do it in, and get to a truth that seems to find  

649
00:54:40,800 --> 00:54:46,680
a pattern or you hear about multiple times and 
then validate that truth and see if that still  

650
00:54:46,680 --> 00:54:52,280
sticks. Have a prototype, do the betas, see if 
the numbers actually work out in your favor. 

651
00:54:52,280 --> 00:54:56,600
I think the other thing is the 
customer obsession needs to also be  

652
00:54:56,600 --> 00:55:01,640
anchored back into does it work for your business? 
Just because a customer wants it, I mean,  

653
00:55:01,640 --> 00:55:05,560
they probably want free products that doesn't 
work for what we're going to be able to serve  

654
00:55:05,560 --> 00:55:12,720
them with and still be a viable business and still 
survive. And so I think I actually used a lot of,  

655
00:55:12,720 --> 00:55:17,560
when we were doing pricing, I used a lot of 
insights from your podcast with Madhavan. That  

656
00:55:17,560 --> 00:55:24,600
was a great, I mean, if I can promo a different 
podcast episode on this one, that was great. 

657
00:55:24,600 --> 00:55:29,600
I think I listened to it twice just to hear it 
a few times, and I think there was an example  

658
00:55:29,600 --> 00:55:39,600
of a water at a fountain is free, a water at a 
hotel is like five bucks, a water on the plane  

659
00:55:39,600 --> 00:55:45,960
is... The context and the price of what you're 
offering somebody changes the value perception  

660
00:55:45,960 --> 00:55:51,080
of what they're getting delivered. And so 
I think that customer obsession needs to  

661
00:55:51,080 --> 00:55:56,560
be just anchored back into the business and the 
business needs and what you can actually offer.  

662
00:55:56,560 --> 00:56:00,440
And so it all needs to be triangulated and 
balanced out. And so it's not just customer  

663
00:56:00,440 --> 00:56:06,600
obsession for the sense of customer obsession, 
but where does that artistry meet the business?

664
00:56:06,600 --> 00:56:10,480
Awesome. That was a great example. We'll link to 
the Madhavan episode, folks that want to check it  

665
00:56:10,480 --> 00:56:15,040
out. And then one very tactical question, how 
do your teams find customers to talk to and  

666
00:56:15,040 --> 00:56:18,600
organize that? Is there anything operationally 
that folks can learn about how you do that?

667
00:56:18,600 --> 00:56:24,080
We do have a UXR team, which is great. We 
have a research team, and so they help us  

668
00:56:24,080 --> 00:56:28,560
make sure that we can... Honestly, the scheduling 
Tetris that has to happen is probably the hardest  

669
00:56:28,560 --> 00:56:34,280
part in a PM schedule because you're going from 
meetings to meetings. So sometimes we'll just have  

670
00:56:34,280 --> 00:56:38,600
dedicated research weeks where we know there's 
a question that we need answered and we need  

671
00:56:38,600 --> 00:56:43,920
to go through that discovery, and so we'll clear 
off our calendars and just book customer calls.  

672
00:56:43,920 --> 00:56:50,680
When it's regular sessions that are happening 
every week, then we try to leverage a central  

673
00:56:50,680 --> 00:56:55,760
team to help us manage those calendar and meeting 
invites and getting people booked. We'll also just  

674
00:56:56,760 --> 00:57:03,320
get in the sidecar of an RM call or a 
sales call or a CS call whenever we can,  

675
00:57:03,320 --> 00:57:07,760
anybody who's doing any sort of research or 
voice of the customer calls, anything like that,  

676
00:57:07,760 --> 00:57:12,880
we're in and we want to hear about it. And 
then we're also looking and just responding  

677
00:57:12,880 --> 00:57:20,360
on X or on email or... We want to hear from 
people. So find us any which way you can.

678
00:57:20,360 --> 00:57:22,400
Okay, cool. And then what 
does RM stand for by the way?

679
00:57:22,400 --> 00:57:24,760
Oh, sorry, sorry. Relationship 
managers, our sales team.

680
00:57:24,760 --> 00:57:26,160
Okay, cool. So like account managers?

681
00:57:26,680 --> 00:57:26,920
Yes.

682
00:57:26,920 --> 00:57:30,840
Awesome. Okay. I'm going to come back to where we 
were. I pushed us off track. I'm going to bring  

683
00:57:30,840 --> 00:57:35,440
us back on track. So we're talking about things 
you've learned about building multi-products,  

684
00:57:35,440 --> 00:57:40,440
additional products at a company. The 
first kind of theme was the org and  

685
00:57:40,440 --> 00:57:46,400
creating barriers almost to pulling resources 
away from these seedling teams into your core.

686
00:57:46,400 --> 00:57:51,480
Yeah, I think the other decisions that we had 
to make that might be helpful to folks was like,  

687
00:57:51,480 --> 00:57:58,280
what are the next products? And so we really 
looked at like, okay, we need to find solutions  

688
00:57:58,280 --> 00:58:04,040
that tie closer to the existing spaces we're in. 
It needs to be an adjacency that's just beyond  

689
00:58:04,040 --> 00:58:08,920
the core. It's not about just building a new 
feature. You are building a new product line,  

690
00:58:08,920 --> 00:58:14,760
so what is that adjacent customer segment 
that would be interested in a deeper,  

691
00:58:14,760 --> 00:58:21,240
more fuller product experience? A good example 
is invoicing. We de-risked that when we were  

692
00:58:21,240 --> 00:58:24,920
thinking about, okay, what's the next set of 
products that we could look at? We looked at  

693
00:58:24,920 --> 00:58:31,960
a bunch of different areas and we're really 
thoughtful around who is our target segment  

694
00:58:31,960 --> 00:58:38,600
or ICP and then who do we want to serve? 
And we saw some work that was interesting. 

695
00:58:38,600 --> 00:58:43,600
Because we had this concept of this product called 
Payment Requests where you could send somebody a  

696
00:58:43,600 --> 00:58:48,560
URL, they could go to that URL and send the money 
that they owe you directly to your bank account.  

697
00:58:48,560 --> 00:58:54,160
That had traction and so that was something that 
we used as a competitive advantage because we're  

698
00:58:54,160 --> 00:58:57,880
like, "Oh, we can talk to people that were 
already doing something that was invoicing,  

699
00:58:57,880 --> 00:59:03,600
which is a request for payment over the web." 
And so we talked to a bunch of those customers.  

700
00:59:03,600 --> 00:59:07,240
We also knew that we had a distribution advantage 
because if we already had people that were using  

701
00:59:07,240 --> 00:59:12,400
this, we could probably get more folks that 
were on Mercury already. We didn't have to  

702
00:59:12,400 --> 00:59:15,920
go find them outside. We didn't have to do a 
full go-to-market effort. We could just kind  

703
00:59:15,920 --> 00:59:20,680
of test out if they had a fuller invoicing 
solution, would they want to use that? 

704
00:59:20,680 --> 00:59:27,040
And so we used that adjacency to our advantage 
and our distribution to our advantage and said,  

705
00:59:27,040 --> 00:59:32,880
"Okay, let's build out these next products that 
are kind of in that same ecosystem or universe  

706
00:59:32,880 --> 00:59:39,360
and see what works and see what sticks." We 
also kind of used that current UX to drive  

707
00:59:39,360 --> 00:59:44,880
that attached to these new products. So on the 
opposite side, like the accounts payable side,  

708
00:59:44,880 --> 00:59:49,720
when you're sending a payment, we highlight Bill 
Pay if you need more complex vendor payments. And  

709
00:59:49,720 --> 00:59:55,320
so it's a really easy way to just fit into the 
natural flow of what a customer is doing anyways  

710
00:59:55,320 --> 01:00:01,400
and say, "Hey, do you actually need something more 
robust? We have something for you. Try it out."

711
01:00:01,400 --> 01:00:07,640
So some attributes you look for is have you 
de-risk that... Basically, you're already  

712
01:00:07,640 --> 01:00:14,560
seeing there's a need here from a baby feature of 
that product. And then do you have a distribution  

713
01:00:14,560 --> 01:00:19,400
advantage essentially? Can you find a way to 
get in front of people in your existing product?

714
01:00:19,400 --> 01:00:21,760
Exactly. That's it.

715
01:00:21,760 --> 01:00:25,760
And then there's probably just like, 
"Damn, is this a big opportunity?" And  

716
01:00:25,760 --> 01:00:28,440
then just thinking about what are 
the biggest opportunities we have.

717
01:00:28,440 --> 01:00:33,160
Right. Yeah, we did all of that kind of like 
pre-work as just is it even viable? And then do  

718
01:00:33,160 --> 01:00:37,720
we have an advantage around that? And I think the 
place that we hit are like, yeah, we already have  

719
01:00:37,720 --> 01:00:42,000
an advantage. This would be... There's a little 
bit less friction in order to get to the escape  

720
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:48,960
velocity that we need. And then right now, I think 
once you've launched, that's one step, that's one  

721
01:00:48,960 --> 01:00:54,280
big hurdle. Then there's the next hurdle, which is 
really trying to find that product market fit and  

722
01:00:54,280 --> 01:00:58,000
that's where we're at now and I think that's 
a really important lesson of don't go from  

723
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:04,080
launch to try to revenue optimize or find that 
efficiency immediately. I think what we really  

724
01:01:04,080 --> 01:01:09,760
want is to give away the second product, the 
third product for free, encourage as much usage  

725
01:01:09,760 --> 01:01:15,320
and engagement and retention to show that there's 
something there, and allow customers to feel good  

726
01:01:15,320 --> 01:01:20,760
about how they would use us in their workflows.
And then once they get to a place where they're  

727
01:01:20,760 --> 01:01:25,960
needing more complexity or needing some areas 
where they could save time and drive some just  

728
01:01:25,960 --> 01:01:31,160
ease of use, then yes, they'd actually be willing 
to pay for it. But it's not like you put this  

729
01:01:31,160 --> 01:01:35,240
paywall in and then automatically just launch 
a product and say, "Now you have to pay us."  

730
01:01:35,240 --> 01:01:40,400
We want to encourage this idea of what worked for 
a core product. We were always free to customers,  

731
01:01:40,400 --> 01:01:44,600
now we had to go to a paid offering. And so 
we want to make sure that people feel good  

732
01:01:44,600 --> 01:01:49,560
about it. We're not overcharging customers that 
are too small and don't want to pay, and we're  

733
01:01:49,560 --> 01:01:55,840
really focusing on the customers that need that 
extra, the heft that comes with these products.

734
01:01:56,920 --> 01:02:01,400
It's interesting because if I reflect back to 
the Madhavan pricing episode, he's actually like,  

735
01:02:01,400 --> 01:02:04,800
"Don't ever discount. Charge exactly what 
